# Advanced Economics O/X
> Core principles of micro and macro economics
@languageCode: en
// Swiq — https://swiq.jiun.dev/set/seed.en.economy-finance.principles/

According to the law of demand, all else equal, when the price of a good rises its quantity demanded tends to fall. | O | The law of demand states that higher prices generally reduce the quantity demanded.
Inflation is a general and sustained increase in prices that reduces the purchasing power of money. | O | Inflation erodes purchasing power as the same money buys fewer goods over time.
Opportunity cost is the combined value of every alternative given up, not just the next-best one. | X | Opportunity cost is the value of the single next-best alternative forgone, not the sum of all alternatives.
Raising the central bank's key interest rate generally tends to cool borrowing, spending, and investment. | O | Higher rates raise borrowing costs, which tends to slow spending and investment.
GDP measures the market value of final goods and services produced within a country over a period. | O | GDP sums the market value of final output produced within a nation's borders in a period.
In a monopoly, many firms compete so that no single firm can influence the price. | X | A monopoly has a single dominant supplier that can influence price; many-firm competition is the opposite.
Supply and demand determine the equilibrium price where quantity supplied equals quantity demanded. | O | At equilibrium the quantity supplied equals the quantity demanded, setting the market price.
Deflation is a sustained fall in the general price level. | O | Deflation is a sustained decrease in prices, which can discourage spending and deepen slumps.
What policy tool does a central bank use to manage inflation by adjusting interest rates and money supply? | 1)Monetary policy 2)Fiscal policy 3)Trade policy 4)Industrial policy | 1 | Monetary policy is run by a central bank to manage money supply, interest rates, and inflation.
Which term describes goods that tend to be bought less as consumer income rises? | 1)Inferior goods 2)Luxury goods 3)Normal goods 4)Public goods | 1 | Demand for inferior goods falls as income rises, unlike normal or luxury goods.
Q: What is the government's use of taxation and spending to influence the economy called? (two words) | A: fiscal policy | Fiscal policy uses government taxing and spending to influence aggregate demand and the economy.
Q: What term describes a general, sustained rise in prices that reduces money's value? | A: inflation | Inflation is a sustained increase in the general price level that lowers purchasing power.
According to comparative advantage, countries gain from trade by specializing in goods they can produce at a lower opportunity cost. | O | Comparative advantage says trade benefits both parties when each specializes where its opportunity cost is lowest.
A price ceiling set below the equilibrium price typically creates a surplus of the good. | X | A binding price ceiling creates a shortage: at the artificially low price, quantity demanded exceeds quantity supplied.
Which measure tracks the average change in prices of a fixed basket of consumer goods and services? | 1)GDP deflator 2)Producer Price Index 3)Consumer Price Index 4)Gini coefficient | 3 | The Consumer Price Index (CPI) measures the average price change of a typical basket of consumer goods and services.
Demand is called elastic when quantity demanded responds strongly to a change in price. | O | Price elasticity measures responsiveness; elastic demand means a small price change causes a large change in quantity demanded.
Public goods, such as national defense, are excludable and rival in consumption. | X | Public goods are non-excludable and non-rival: no one can be barred from them, and one person's use does not reduce another's.
Q: What term describes how easily an asset can be converted into cash without losing value? | A: liquidity;asset liquidity | Liquidity is the ease with which an asset can be turned into cash; cash itself is the most liquid asset.
Nominal GDP is measured at current prices, while real GDP adjusts for inflation. | O | Real GDP removes the effect of price changes, so it reflects changes in actual output rather than inflation.
In a progressive tax system, everyone pays the same percentage of their income in tax. | X | A progressive tax charges higher rates on higher incomes; a flat (proportional) tax applies the same rate to everyone.
In which market structure do many sellers offer identical products, so no single seller can influence the price? | 1)Monopoly 2)Perfect competition 3)Oligopoly 4)Monopolistic competition | 2 | Perfect competition features many price-taking firms selling identical products with free market entry and exit.
Marginal cost is the additional cost of producing one more unit of output. | O | Marginal cost measures the extra cost of one additional unit and guides a firm's optimal output decision.
Stagflation refers to a period of high economic growth combined with low inflation. | X | Stagflation is the opposite: stagnant growth and high unemployment occurring together with high inflation, as in the 1970s.
Q: What is the rate at which one currency can be traded for another called? (two words) | A: exchange rate;the exchange rate;currency exchange rate;foreign exchange rate | The exchange rate is the price of one currency in terms of another and shifts with supply and demand in currency markets.
A negative externality occurs when a transaction imposes costs on third parties, as with pollution. | O | Externalities are costs or benefits that fall on outsiders; pollution is the classic negative externality.
When a country's currency depreciates, its exports generally become more expensive for foreign buyers. | X | Depreciation makes exports cheaper for foreigners and imports more expensive at home, which tends to boost export demand.
Which economist wrote 'The Wealth of Nations' (1776) and described the 'invisible hand' of markets? | 1)John Maynard Keynes 2)Karl Marx 3)David Ricardo 4)Adam Smith | 4 | Adam Smith's 'The Wealth of Nations' founded classical economics and used the invisible hand to describe self-regulating markets.
Diminishing marginal utility means each additional unit of a good tends to give less extra satisfaction than the one before. | O | As consumption increases, the added satisfaction from each extra unit typically falls — the law of diminishing marginal utility.
The unemployment rate counts everyone without a job, including people who are not looking for work. | X | The unemployment rate only counts jobless people actively seeking work; those not searching are outside the labor force.
Q: What is a government payment that lowers producers' costs to encourage the output of a good called? | A: subsidy;a subsidy;subsidies;government subsidy | A subsidy is a government payment or tax break that lowers production costs to encourage the supply of a good or service.
An oligopoly is a market dominated by a small number of large firms. | O | In an oligopoly a few large firms dominate, so each firm's decisions strongly affect its rivals.
A budget deficit occurs when a government's revenue exceeds its spending. | X | A deficit means spending exceeds revenue; when revenue exceeds spending, the government runs a surplus.
Which term is commonly defined informally as two consecutive quarters of falling real GDP? | 1)Depression 2)Hyperinflation 3)Recession 4)Stagnation | 3 | A recession is a broad economic downturn, often informally identified as two straight quarters of declining real GDP.
Rational decision-making should ignore sunk costs, since they cannot be recovered. | O | Sunk costs are already spent and unrecoverable, so rational choices should weigh only future costs and benefits.
According to the law of supply, producers generally offer less of a good for sale as its price rises. | X | The law of supply says the opposite: higher prices make production more profitable, so quantity supplied tends to rise.
Q: What is the strategy of spreading investments across different assets to reduce risk called? | A: diversification;portfolio diversification;diversifying;diversify | Diversification spreads money across varied assets so that losses in one holding are offset by others, lowering overall risk.
